-- Japan's Stocks Decline, Led by Banks; Nintendo Tumbles on Profit Forecast
-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a
-- 2010-09-30T08:05:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-30/japan-s-stocks-fluctuate-as-banks-drop-trading-houses-rise-on-oil-metals.html
Japanese  stocks  fell, led by
electronics makers and banks, amid concern that Europe’s debt
crisis will slow a recovery of the global economy?and after
Nintendo Co. tumbled, dragging down parts suppliers.  Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group Inc. and Sumitomo Mitsui
Financial Group Inc., Japan’s two biggest banks by market value,
slid at least 3.5 percent. Fanuc Ltd., a robot maker that gets
almost 20 percent of its revenue in Europe, slid 2.8 percent.
Sony Corp., an electronics maker that earns more than 40 percent
of its revenue from the U.S. and Europe, fell 2.4 percent as the
yen rose.  Nintendo , the world’s largest maker of portable video-
game machines, plunged 9.3 percent after cutting its profit and
dividend forecasts.  “People in the market are running away from risk assets
after the Irish announcement,” said  Ayako Sera , who helps
oversee about $310 billion in Tokyo as a strategist at Sumitomo
Trust & Banking Co. “Investors are concerned about financial
risks and credit ratings.”  The  Nikkei 225 Stock Average  sank 2 percent to 9,369.35 as
of the close in Tokyo. The broader Topix declined 2.1 percent to
829.51, with more than nine times as many shares declining as
advancing. The Nikkei 225 dropped 0.1 in the quarter ending
today and the Topix slid 1.4 percent. For the month, both gauges
gained the most since March.  Stocks extended declines in the afternoon after Ireland’s
central bank said  Anglo Irish Bank Corp.  and Allied Irish Banks
Plc may need up to 14.4 billion euros ($19.6 billion) in extra
capital and as the yen strengthened.  Banks Drop  The Topix has dropped 17 percent from its high this year on
April 15 as Europe’s debt crisis, China’s steps to curb property
prices and concern about the pace of U.S. economic growth have
hurt confidence in a global recovery. Stocks in the index trade
at 14.8 times estimated earnings on average, compared with 13.8
times for the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and 12 times for the
 Stoxx Europe 600 Index .  Mitsubishi UFJ slumped 3.7 percent to 389 yen and its
closest rival Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group Inc. sank 3.9
percent to 2,432 yen. Banks were the second-heaviest drag on the
Topix among the gauge’s 33 industry groups, following
electronics makers.  European Central Bank President  Jean-Claude Trichet  said
tougher capital rules will be a “cornerstone” of a revamped
financial system. The so-called Basel III rules are also
“global minimum standards and national regulators or
supervisors can set tougher standards if they deem that
appropriate,” Trichet said during a dinner speech in Brussels
yesterday.  Spain had its top credit rating cut to Aa1 by Moody’s
Investors Service with a stable outlook, the ratings company
said in a filing after the market closed in Tokyo today.  Nintendo Tumbles  Fanuc slipped 2.8 percent to 10,630 yen, the biggest single
drag on the Nikkei 225. Sony slumped 2.4 percent to 2,581 yen,
the biggest drop since Aug. 31.  The yen appreciated to as high as 83.23 against the dollar
in Tokyo, compared with 83.77 at the opening of stock trading
today. Against the euro, Japan’s currency strengthened to 112.98
from 114.13. A stronger yen reduces overseas income at Japanese
companies when converted into their home currency.  Nintendo tumbled 9.3 percent to 20,860 yen in Osaka trading,
the  biggest single contributor  to the Topix’s drop, followed by
Mitsubishi UFJ.  The company slashed its full-year net-income forecast 55
percent to 90 billion yen ($1.1 billion) and said it won’t
release its new 3DS handheld game player in time for the year-
end holiday season. Nintendo also cut its planned full-year
dividend to 550 yen from 830 yen. The company paid 930 yen a
year earlier.  Electronic Parts Makers  Electronic parts makers that supply Nintendo declined.
Mitsumi Electric Co. lost 7.2 percent to 1,280 yen, the biggest
drop in the Nikkei 225. Also, Mitsumi’s target price was cut to
1,450 yen from 1,490 yen by Goldman Sachs Group Inc. Hosiden
Corp. tumbled 12 percent to 756 yen, the most since October 2008.  The  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  fell 0.3 percent yesterday
in New York, trimming its best September rally since 1939. U.S.
banks followed European lenders’ decline yesterday on concern
the region’s most-indebted nations will struggle to finance
budget deficits.  More than 100,000 protesters descended on Brussels
yesterday before a meeting between union members and European
Commission President  Jose Barroso , organizers said. Spanish
workers disrupted transportation and television broadcasts in
the first general strike in eight years. In Athens, rail,
communications and port workers staged strikes. Police in Dublin
made an arrest after a truck damaged the front gates of the
parliament building.  Mitsui O.S.K. Lines Ltd. , operator of the world’s largest
merchant fleet, sank 4 percent to 525 yen after Citigroup Inc.
cut the shipping line to “hold” from “buy,” citing possible
weakness of bulk demand next fiscal year or later. Kawasaki
Kisen Kaisha Ltd., Japan’s third-biggest shipping line, fell 2.2
percent to 314 yen after its stock price estimate was lowered by
325 yen from 370 yen by Citigroup.  To contact the reporters for this story:
